        heading: 'The Role Of Aggregates In Concrete',
        body: 'Aggregates are the most important component of concrete by volume, typically making up 60 to 80 percent of the total mix. Despite being often called the filler, aggregates play an active and critical role in determining concrete performance. They provide dimensional stability, reduce shrinkage, improve durability and contribute to the overall strength of the hardened concrete. The properties of aggregates — their size, shape, texture, gradation, strength and cleanliness — directly influence every aspect of concrete quality including workability, strength, durability and appearance. In Tanzania, where concrete is used for everything from small residential foundations to major infrastructure projects, understanding how aggregates affect concrete quality is essential for achieving successful construction outcomes.'
