        body: 'Impurities in aggregates can seriously damage concrete quality. Clay and silt particles coat aggregate surfaces, preventing proper bonding with cement paste and increasing water demand. Organic matter such as leaves, roots and humus can interfere with cement hydration and cause setting problems. Salts in aggregates can lead to efflorescence and corrosion of steel reinforcement. Sulphates and chlorides can cause chemical reactions that weaken and crack concrete over time. Soft particles like shale and coal create weak spots in the concrete. In Tanzania, the risk of aggregate contamination varies by source — river sand may contain organic matter and silt, while quarry products may contain dust and clay. Washing aggregates removes most impurities, which is why Tanzibaba uses washed sand and clean crushed stone for all concrete production.'
